    blueprintArea: "TCP-II",
    topic: "S Corporation Taxation",
    subtopic: "S Corp Termination Events",
    difficulty: "medium",
    skillLevel: "Application",
    question: "An S corporation election is involuntarily terminated when:",
    options: ["The corporation files Form 1120-S late","Any of the eligibility requirements cease to be met — including exceeding 100 shareholders, having an ineligible shareholder (partnership, C corporation, nonresident alien), creating a second class of stock, or having excess passive investment income for 3 consecutive years while holding accumulated C corporation E&P","The corporation earns a profit","A shareholder sells stock to another individual"],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "IRC §1362(d) Termination of S Corporation Election: Voluntary revocation (§1362(d)(1)): shareholders holding more than 50% of issued and outstanding shares consent to revocation; effective date can be specified or defaults to beginning of next tax year (or current year if filed on or before the 15th day of the 3rd month). Involuntary termination (§1362(d)(2)): election terminates automatically if any §1361 requirement is violated — exceeds 100 shareholders, ineligible shareholder acquires stock (partnership, C corporation, nonresident alien, certain trusts), second class of stock is created (stock with different distribution or liquidation rights), or the corporation becomes an ineligible corporation type. Effective date: the day the terminating event occurs; the S corporation has two short tax years (S corporation short year + C corporation short year). Passive income termination (§1362(d)(3)): if the S corporation has accumulated E&P from C corporation years AND passive investment income exceeds 25% of gross receipts for 3 consecutive tax years. Inadvertent termination relief (§1362(f)): IRS may waive a termination if it was inadvertent, steps were taken promptly to correct the problem, and the corporation and shareholders agree to treatment as if the election had been continuously in effect. Waiting period: if S election is terminated (voluntary or involuntary), the corporation generally cannot re-elect S status for 5 years without IRS consent (§1362(g)).",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is WRONG - Filing Form 1120-S late can result in penalties, but it does not automatically terminate the S corporation election. The IRS may assess penalties for late filing, but the S corporation status remains intact unless other termination events occur.",
      1: "Why option B is CORRECT - An S corporation election is involuntarily terminated if it fails to meet any of the eligibility requirements outlined in IRC §1361. These requirements ensure the entity remains a small business corporation, and violating them triggers automatic termination from the date of the violation.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - Earning a profit, in itself, does not terminate an S corporation election. The profitability of the business has no bearing on its S corporation status, as long as it continues to meet all eligibility requirements.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - A shareholder selling stock to another individual does not automatically terminate the S corporation election, unless the new shareholder is an ineligible shareholder type (e.g., a C corporation, partnership, or nonresident alien) or the sale causes the corporation to exceed the 100-shareholder limit.",
    },
    educational: "S corporations offer pass-through taxation, but maintaining this status requires strict adherence to eligibility rules. Violating these rules, such as exceeding the shareholder limit or having an ineligible shareholder, can lead to involuntary termination, effectively reverting the entity to a C corporation for tax purposes. Understanding these rules is crucial for both maintaining S corporation status and advising clients.",
    examTip: "Pay close attention to the specific eligibility requirements for S corporations; a seemingly minor violation can have significant tax consequences.",
    memoryAid: "Remember the acronym 'S.I.N.' for S-Corp Involuntary Termination: Shareholders (exceeding limit or ineligible), Income (excess passive with C-Corp E&P), and Stock (second class).",
    reference: "IRC §1362(d); §1361",
