    options: ["An ESBT cannot hold S corporation stock","An ESBT may have multiple current beneficiaries and may accumulate income — however, the S corporation income portion is taxed at the trust level at the highest individual tax rate (37%) rather than flowing through to beneficiaries","An ESBT must distribute all income currently","An ESBT may only have corporate beneficiaries"],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "IRC §1361(e) Electing Small Business Trust (ESBT): Key differences from QSST: (1) Multiple beneficiaries permitted — can have many individual beneficiaries (must be individuals, estates, or charities), (2) Income accumulation allowed — no requirement to distribute income currently, (3) Corpus distributions — may be made to any beneficiary. ESBT tax treatment: the trust is bifurcated into two portions: (a) S corporation portion — all S corporation income items are taxed within the trust at the highest individual marginal rate (currently 37%); no deductions are allowed against this portion except state and local income taxes and administrative expenses directly related to the S corporation stock; capital gains from sale of S corp stock are included in this portion, (b) Non-S corporation portion — all other trust income taxed under normal trust rules (compressed brackets, income distribution deduction available). Each potential current beneficiary counts as one shareholder for the 100-shareholder limit. Election: trustee makes the election (not the beneficiary, unlike QSST). ESBT cannot have a nonresident alien as a potential current beneficiary. No exempt organizations as beneficiaries (except charitable organizations). ESBT is preferred when: grantor wants flexibility in distributions, multiple beneficiaries exist, or income accumulation is desired — at the cost of being taxed at the highest rate.",
