    correctAnswer: 2,
    explanation: "IRC §408A(d)(3): Roth IRA conversion: taxable event. The amount converted from traditional to Roth is included in ordinary income (to the extent it represents deductible contributions and earnings). The 10% early withdrawal penalty does NOT apply to conversions (but applies if converted amounts are withdrawn within 5 years and taxpayer is under 59½). No income limit for conversions (the income limit for conversion was eliminated in 2010). \"Backdoor Roth\" strategy: make nondeductible traditional IRA contribution → convert to Roth. Pro-rata rule (§408(d)(2)): if the taxpayer has ANY traditional IRA with pre-tax money, the conversion is taxed proportionally (cannot cherry-pick only after-tax money). Roth IRA: no RMDs during the owner's lifetime (Roth 401(k) RMDs eliminated by SECURE 2.0 starting 2024).",
