    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "IRC §704(b) / Reg. §1.704-1(b) (Substantial Economic Effect): Two-part test: (1) Economic effect (3 requirements — \"safe harbor\"): (a) Capital accounts must be maintained in accordance with Reg. §1.704-1(b)(2)(iv). (b) Liquidating distributions must be in accordance with positive capital account balances. (c) Deficit capital account restoration (DCA) obligation OR \"alternate test for economic effect\" (qualified income offset). (2) Substantiality: the allocation must have a reasonable possibility of substantially affecting dollar amounts independent of tax consequences. \"Shifting allocations\" (net zero effect among partners) and \"transitory allocations\" (offset by subsequent allocations) fail substantiality. If allocation lacks substantial economic effect: reallocated according to partners' interests in the partnership (PIP) — economic arrangement determined by IRS. Target allocations: maintain capital accounts → allocate items to achieve target balances.",
