    question: "An S corporation shareholder's stock basis is adjusted annually in which order?",
    options: ["Losses first, then income","Increased for: (1) income items (separately and non-separately stated), (2) excess depletion deduction; then decreased for: (3) non-dividend distributions, (4) non-deductible non-capital expenses, (5) deductible losses and deductions; basis cannot go below zero","No adjustments are ever needed","Distributions first, then income and losses"],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "IRC §1367 S Corporation Shareholder Basis — Annual ordering rules: Step 1 — INCREASES: (a) separately stated income items (capital gains, §1231 gains, tax-exempt income, etc.), (b) non-separately stated income (ordinary business income), (c) excess depletion deduction over basis in the property. Step 2 — DECREASES (after increases): (a) non-dividend distributions (§1368) — reduce basis but not below zero; excess distribution is capital gain, (b) non-deductible, non-capital expenses (e.g., 50% meals disallowance, penalties, expenses related to tax-exempt income), (c) deductible losses and deductions (separately and non-separately stated). Why ordering matters: income items increase basis BEFORE distributions reduce it — this allows more distributions to be received tax-free (return of basis) and provides more basis for deducting losses. Key differences from partnerships: S corp basis is NOT increased by entity-level debt (only shareholder loans to the corporation increase debt basis under §1366(d)(1)(B)). Excess losses: suspended and carried forward indefinitely.",
