    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "IRC §243 Dividends Received Deduction (DRD): Deduction percentage based on ownership: (1) Less than 20% ownership of the paying corporation: 50% DRD, (2) 20% to less than 80% ownership: 65% DRD, (3) 80% or more ownership (affiliated group member): 100% DRD (§243(a)(3)). Taxable income limitation: the DRD cannot exceed the specified percentage of taxable income (computed without additional NOL deduction, DRD, and other adjustments). Exception to taxable income limitation: if claiming the full DRD would create or increase an NOL, the taxable income limitation does not apply (i.e., full DRD is allowed). Purpose: reduce triple taxation — the paying corporation already paid tax on the income, and the receiving corporation's dividend income should not be fully taxed again before flowing to individual shareholders. Qualified dividends from foreign corporations and certain debt-financed portfolio stock have different rules.",
