    question: "A C corporation's charitable contribution deduction is limited to:",
    options: ["60% of adjusted gross income","10% of taxable income computed before the charitable deduction, DRD, NOL carryback, and capital loss carryback — excess contributions can be carried forward for 5 years","25% of taxable income","50% of gross receipts"],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "IRC §170(b)(2) Corporate Charitable Deduction: Limit: 10% of taxable income computed without regard to: the charitable contribution deduction itself, the dividends received deduction (DRD), any NOL carryback, any capital loss carryback. Carryforward: excess charitable contributions can be carried forward for 5 years (FIFO — oldest excess used first). Special rules for property contributions: appreciated capital gain property: deduct FMV (no reduction for built-in gain) — but 10% limit still applies; ordinary income property: deduct the lesser of FMV or adjusted basis (FMV reduced by ordinary income that would have been recognized); inventory contributions for care of the ill, needy, or infants: enhanced deduction = adjusted basis + 50% of unrealized appreciation (limited to 2× adjusted basis). Accrual method: a C corporation may elect to deduct contributions authorized by the board of directors before year-end if paid within 2.5 months after year-end (§170(a)(2)). Note: these rules differ significantly from individual charitable deduction rules (60%/30%/20% AGI limits, different carryforward period).",
