      1: "Why option B is CORRECT - S corporation distributions avoid FICA taxes (Social Security and Medicare), creating an incentive for officer-shareholders to take distributions instead of a reasonable salary. The IRS requires reasonable compensation to prevent this tax avoidance.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - S corporation distributions are generally *not* tax-exempt. They are typically taxed to the extent they exceed the shareholder's basis in their stock.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - The IRS doesn't mandate higher salaries for all employees universally. Their focus is on ensuring reasonable compensation for officer-shareholders in S corporations to prevent payroll tax avoidance.",
