    question: "A taxpayer has a $60,000 net operating loss (NOL) from a sole proprietorship in 2024. The taxpayer also has $100,000 of W-2 income. Under current law, how is the NOL treated?",
    options: ["The NOL offsets up to 80% of taxable income ($80,000), leaving at least 20% taxable. The full $60,000 NOL is used since it is less than the 80% limit","The NOL offsets 100% of taxable income with no limitation","The NOL cannot offset W-2 income — only future business income","The NOL carries back 2 years before carrying forward"],
    correctAnswer: 0,
    explanation: "Under current law (post-TCJA, post-CARES), NOLs arising in tax years beginning after December 31, 2020 may offset only 80% of taxable income in the carryforward year. NOLs generally carry forward indefinitely but cannot be carried back (the CARES Act 5-year carryback applied only to 2018-2020 NOLs). Here, 80% of $100,000 = $80,000 limit. Since the $60,000 NOL is less than $80,000, the full $60,000 is used. Remaining taxable income = $40,000.",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is CORRECT - Net operating losses (NOLs) generated after 2020 can offset up to 80% of taxable income. Since the $60,000 NOL is less than 80% of the $100,000 W-2 income ($80,000), the entire NOL can be used.",
      1: "Why option B is WRONG - While the CARES Act temporarily allowed 100% offset, current law (post-2020) limits NOL deductions to 80% of taxable income.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - NOLs can offset various types of income, including W-2 income, subject to the 80% limitation.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - The carryback provision for NOLs generally applies only to NOLs arising in tax years 2018-2020 under the CARES Act; current law generally allows indefinite carryforward only.",
    },
    educational: "A net operating loss (NOL) occurs when a business's deductions exceed its income. NOLs can be used to reduce taxable income in other years, providing a tax benefit. Understanding the rules regarding NOL carryforwards and carrybacks, as well as the percentage limitations, is crucial for tax planning and compliance.",
    examTip: "Pay close attention to the year the NOL was generated, as this determines the applicable carryforward/carryback rules and percentage limitations.",
    memoryAid: "80% Rule: Remember 'Eighty is Enough' for NOL offsets after 2020.",
    reference: "IRC Sections 671-679",
