    explanation: "The general business credit is the sum of the research credit and the work opportunity credit. The research credit is calculated as 20% of qualified research expenses, and the work opportunity credit is calculated as 40% of qualified first-year wages. In this case:\nResearch Credit = 0.20 * $250,000 = $50,000\nWork Opportunity Credit = 0.40 * $100,000 = $40,000\nTotal General Business Credit = $50,000 + $40,000 = $90,000\nThe general business credit is limited to the net income tax less the greater of (1) the tentative minimum tax or (2) 25% of net income tax over $25,000. \n$50,000 - GREATER($60,000, (0.25 * ($50,000 - $25,000)))\n$50,000 - GREATER($60,000, $6,250)\n$50,000 - $60,000 = -$10,000. Therefore the general business credit is limited to the net income tax. \nThe general business credit is limited to the amount of the net income tax not exceeding $25,000 plus 75% of the net income tax exceeding $25,000. \n$25,000 + 0.75($50,000-$25,000) = $43,750. \nAdditionally, the general business credit cannot exceed the prior year's tax liability. \nTherefore the maximum general business credit is the smallest of $90,000, $43,750, and $40,000 + the research credit. \n$43,750 + research credit carryback = 50000+40000= 90000 -> 43750. Limit to the net income tax not exceeding 25000 + 75% of the net income tax exceeding 25000. So 25000 + 0.75(25000) = 43750. Since the prior year liability was 40000 we add 25% to account for the research credit carryback. \n40000* 0.25 = 10000 -> 43750 + 10000 = 52500",
